{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492913"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:49:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:49:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1184"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1184"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.38,0.12,0.09,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38791"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1184"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23136"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1158"},{"type":"tags","id":"2043"},{"type":"tags","id":"2044"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5491"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6957"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38791"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 37-year-old woman presents with a three month history of an intermittent and spontaneous blood-stained discharge from her right nipple. She does not use any regular medication, is pre-menopausal and she is not pregnant. Clinical examination is normal, apart from some blood-stained discharge from a single duct on the right nipple. Mammography and ultrasound examination are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Review in six months","Microdochectomy","Major duct excision","Wide local excision with sentinel node biopsy","Mastectomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of spontaneous nipple discharge, most likely due to \u003Cstrong\u003Eintraductal papilloma.\u003C/strong\u003E Intraductal papilloma is the most common cause of bloody nipple discharge in young patients. It is a benign condition in which there is growth of epithelial fronds in the milk duct. It is important to order mammography and ultrasound for any patient presenting with spontaneous nipple discharge to exclude an underlying malignancy. Intraduct papillomas can be very small and easily missed on mammography and ultrasound examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurgical removal of the affected duct, also called \u003Cstrong\u003Emicrodochectomy,\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line management of intraductal papilloma. Although intraductal papilloma has low malignant potential, surgical removal is recommended to establish the diagnosis, exclude malignancy, and for symptom relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReview in six months\u003C/strong\u003E is not the recommended treatment plan. A more active intervention is required to stop the discharge and exclude malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWide local excision with sentinel node biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for malignant breast lesions, which is not the case in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMastectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary in this patient as the mammography and ultrasound results are all normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMajor duct excision, \u003C/strong\u003Ewhere all of the main ducts behind the nipple are excised,\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis rarely necessary in young, pre-menopausal patients as it compromises their ability to breast feed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intraductal papilloma is the most common cause of bloody nipple discharge in young patients."],"references":["The New South Wales Breast Cancer Institute. Nipple Discharge. Australian Family Physician Vol. 34, No. 5; May 2005. Viewed at October 2022. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/98adc6c4-a7de-4e51-9610-6d8a7907bd20/200505nswbci.pdf","Dixon JM, editor. ABC of breast diseases. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2012 Oct 8. Viewed at October 2022. Available at: https://www.melbournebreastcancersurgery.com.au/wp-content/themes/ypo-theme/pdf/benign-breast-conditions.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23136"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1184"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"23136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/23136"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-08-08T20:38:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-08-08T20:38:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1184"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38791"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"ta